#Methodology

-Joined Textbooks to AuthorTextbookLink to connect books with author IDs
-Joined AuthorTextbookLink to Authors to identify author names
-Joined Courses to Textbooks to connect curriculum with assigned books
-Used LEFT JOIN when all courses needed to be retained, even if textbook or author data was missing
-Used INNER JOIN when only complete matches were needed

#Followed a structured approach:

Identify business question → Determine table relationships → Select join type → Filter results → Interpret business value

#Key Insights

-Multiple joins make it possible to trace textbooks from curriculum to authors
-INNER JOIN is useful when the goal is to analyze only complete textbook-author-course relationships
-LEFT JOIN is useful when all courses must be retained, even if some lack textbook or author assignments
-Curriculum and textbook mapping can reveal sales opportunities tied to subject area and grade level
-Breaking multi-join problems into smaller steps improves readability and accuracy

#Recommendations

-Use curriculum-to-textbook mapping to support targeted textbook sales outreach
-Review current economics materials regularly to promote updated editions
-Track author associations across subjects and grade levels to better understand content usage
-Continue using structured join logic when analyzing educational publishing data

